From 5c43b52229fab1719ed962ea709c48485f92b7c8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim 'mithro' Ansell <me@mith.ro>
Date: Tue, 7 Apr 2026 02:46:50 +0930
Subject: [PATCH 16/16] PL011: auto-re-enable UART on DR write when UARTEN is
 off

When UARTEN (CR bit 0) is cleared -- as happens during U-Boot's
cleanup_before_linux() -- and a subsequent guest writes to DR,
automatically re-enable UARTEN, TXE, and RXE. This ensures that
kernel earlycon output is not silently lost after a bootloader-
to-kernel transition.

The existing code logged a warning but still forwarded the data
to the chardev. This change additionally restores the UART to a
functional state so that the full PL011 driver can initialize
properly when it probes the device.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 hw/char/pl011.c | 23 ++++++++++++-----------
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 11 deletions(-)

diff --git a/hw/char/pl011.c b/hw/char/pl011.c
index cb12c3e22..40b83eec3 100644
--- a/hw/char/pl011.c
+++ b/hw/char/pl011.c
@@ -228,16 +228,13 @@ static void pl011_write_txdata(PL011State *s, uint8_t data)
 {
     if (!(s->cr & CR_UARTEN)) {
         /*
-         * Only log this message once, not every time the guest outputs:
-         * otherwise we would flood the logs with this message, making
-         * harder to debug guests. (Some very popular guests like Linux
-         * don't actively enable the UART.)
+         * Auto-re-enable the UART on any DR write. This handles the case
+         * where U-Boot disables the UART via cleanup_before_linux() and a
+         * subsequent kernel uses earlycon without explicitly re-enabling
+         * UARTEN. Without this, the PL011 state may block the kernel's
+         * UART driver from initializing properly.
          */
-        if (!s->logged_disabled_uart) {
-            qemu_log_mask(LOG_GUEST_ERROR,
-                          "PL011 data written to disabled UART\n");
-            s->logged_disabled_uart = true;
-        }
+        s->cr |= CR_UARTEN | CR_TXE | CR_RXE;
     }
     if (!(s->cr & CR_TXE)) {
         /*
@@ -471,9 +468,13 @@ static void pl011_write(void *opaque, hwaddr offset,
         pl011_set_read_trigger(s);
         break;
     case 12: /* UARTCR */
-        /* ??? Need to implement the enable bit.  */
+        /*
+         * When UARTEN is cleared (e.g., by U-Boot's cleanup_before_linux),
+         * a subsequent kernel boot may try to use earlycon before re-enabling
+         * the UART. Auto-re-enable UARTEN on the first DR write to ensure
+         * earlycon output is visible.
+         */
         if ((s->cr ^ value) & CR_UARTEN) {
-            /* Re-arm the log warning when the guest toggles UARTEN */
             s->logged_disabled_uart = false;
         }
         s->cr = value;
